      "note_no": "62",
      "note": "The phrase iswadda wajhuhu (lit., \"his face became black\" or \"dark\") is used idiomatically to describe a face expressive of grief or ignominy (cf. 16:58), just as its opposite, ibyadda wajhuhu (lit., \"his face became white\" or \"shining\") describes a countenance expressive of happiness or justified pride: cf. 2:106 - \"some faces will shine [with happiness] and some faces will be dark [with grief]\". Apart from this, both phrases have also a tropical significance, namely, \"he became [or \"felt\"] disgraced\", resp. \"honoured\". - As regards the \"inventing of lies about God\" spoken of in this verse, see note 37 above."
